<subSubSection id="BB4D741D51134C7E70E2E146A9485D7B" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="63F15AA30963387320765883AECDAA4E" pageNumber="47">
The amphiamerican sea catfish genus 
<taxonomicName id="6F70D502845F95EE28FB97F194289A58" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:086E7B0F-D030-44BD-9DCC-8CAEB178CBAA" class="Actinopterygii" family="Ariidae" genus="Notarius" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Notarius Gill 1863:171" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="47" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Notarius Gill</taxonomicName>
was recently revised by Betancur-R. and Acero P. (2004). 
<taxonomicName id="C43C786ADA6ECEB71975246D926BB57D" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:086E7B0F-D030-44BD-9DCC-8CAEB178CBAA" class="Actinopterygii" family="Ariidae" genus="Notarius" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Notarius Gill 1863:171" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="47" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Notarius</taxonomicName>
includes at least 14 species, with seven distributed in the eastern Pacific (EP). The monophyly of the genus is strongly supported by molecular evidence obtained from the sequences of five mitochondrial genes and one nuclear gene [3900 base pairs (bp)] (Betancur-R., 2003; Betancur-R. and Acero P., 2004). This claim was not supported by Kailola (2004), who placed the species of 
<taxonomicName id="34F312D3E380A03F8BB1A0622BF09E1C" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:086E7B0F-D030-44BD-9DCC-8CAEB178CBAA" class="Actinopterygii" family="Ariidae" genus="Notarius" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Notarius Gill 1863:171" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="47" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Notarius</taxonomicName>
sensu Betancur-R. and Acero P. (2004) in the genera 
<taxonomicName id="5CD2FCEB0450B6B68D54799A7D46A427" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:3F1F6AF2-6F38-42C0-9C82-C1468F19FAF0" class="Actinopterygii" family="Ariidae" genus="Hemiarius" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Hemiarius Bleeker 1862:7, 29" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="47" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Hemiarius Bleeker</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="D59EFE0407427663AACFE588EA458AFD" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:5E7E77C5-A476-46EF-A160-CBAF0EC843ED" class="Actinopterygii" family="Ariidae" genus="Ariopsis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Ariopsis Gill 1861:56" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="47" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Ariopsis Gill</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="E7E54B0931EB0C40DD33D5277846BB07" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:347CE897-3860-4DA6-85B8-033B2318B81A" class="Actinopterygii" family="Ariidae" genus="Aspistor" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Aspistor Jordan &amp; Evermann 1898:2763" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="47" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Aspistor Jordan &amp; Evermann</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName id="16A96973083D1EDADBF1C94B6681581E" class="Actinopterygii" family="Ariidae" genus="Sciades" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="47" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
Sciades 
<normalizedToken id="276BFF486E51B8799375B084D58BF5AD" originalValue="Müller">Mueller</normalizedToken>
&amp; Troschel
</taxonomicName>
, as well as two species recognized as incertae sedis (Table 1). It is noteworthy, however, that none of the species assigned by Betancur-R. and Acero P. (2004) in 
<taxonomicName id="879ED91619DB4384C1A9377F8EF9E19F" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:086E7B0F-D030-44BD-9DCC-8CAEB178CBAA" class="Actinopterygii" family="Ariidae" genus="Notarius" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Notarius Gill 1863:171" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="47" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Notarius</taxonomicName>
were included in Kailola (2004)’s phylogenetic analysis. Marceniuk and Ferraris (2003), based on the results of Marceniuk’s (2003) unpublished dissertation, also proposed a different classification scheme for New World ariids, placing most of the species of 
<taxonomicName id="307BAEFC8443B232F95E34EA3E2D3F0D" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:086E7B0F-D030-44BD-9DCC-8CAEB178CBAA" class="Actinopterygii" family="Ariidae" genus="Notarius" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Notarius Gill 1863:171" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="47" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Notarius</taxonomicName>
sensu Betancur-R. and Acero P. (2004) in 
<taxonomicName id="6A3A71ADCE592A778D9919DBAB3C69B0" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:086E7B0F-D030-44BD-9DCC-8CAEB178CBAA" class="Actinopterygii" family="Ariidae" genus="Notarius" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Notarius Gill 1863:171" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="47" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Notarius</taxonomicName>
(only four species), 
<taxonomicName id="0FB1287F46B8CF3825BC8FC6C9035B17" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:347CE897-3860-4DA6-85B8-033B2318B81A" class="Actinopterygii" family="Ariidae" genus="Aspistor" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Aspistor Jordan &amp; Evermann 1898:2763" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="47" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Aspistor</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="3351A97683C67FCAFB9DACE4A7560AA2" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:830D572B-79ED-4DBD-84EC-A10E3E7E748C" class="Actinopterygii" family="Ariidae" genus="Arius" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Arius Valenciennes 1840:53" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="47" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Arius Valenciennes</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName id="4691B45D425BA6A6047F68329A5E0142" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:16E97498-AAE2-424A-B158-8DE52FB40A5E" class="Actinopterygii" family="Ariidae" genus="Hexanematichthys" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Hexanematichthys Bleeker 1858:2" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="47" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Hexanematichthys Bleeker</taxonomicName>
(Table 1). In summary, despite the recent efforts to resolve the taxonomy of the Ariidae, its generic nomenclature is still unstable.
</paragraph>
